a("Battle of Poltava","1709-06-27","1709-06-27","Ukraine",["Battle","Great Northern War"],"The Battle of Poltava in 1709 was the Great Northern War's decisive engagement. Peter the Great's reformed Russian army crushed Charles XII's Swedes, marking Russia's emergence and Sweden's decline as a major European power.",[["1708","Charles invades Russia"],["1708","Supply train destroyed at Lesnaya"],["1709","Harsh winter devastates Swedes"],["1709-06-27","Battle of Poltava"],["1709","Swedish army destroyed"],["1709","Charles flees to Ottomans"]]);
a("Battle of Plassey","1757-06-23","1757-06-23","India",["Battle","Colonial War"],"The Battle of Plassey in 1757 established British East India Company rule in India. Clive's 3,000 defeated 50,000 through Mir Jafar's treachery. The victory is considered the beginning of British colonial rule in India.",[["1756","Nawab captures Calcutta"],["1757","Clive conspires with Mir Jafar"],["1757-06-23","Battle at Plassey"],["1757-06-23","Mir Jafar doesn't fight"],["1757-06-23","Nawab's army collapses"],["1757","British control Bengal"]]);
a("First Battle of Panipat","1526-04-21","1526-04-21","India",["Battle","Early Modern War"],"The First Battle of Panipat in 1526 established the Mughal Empire when Babur's 12,000 defeated Ibrahim Lodi's 100,000 using artillery and innovative tactics. The victory founded one of India's greatest empires.",[["1519","Babur raids India"],["1526-04-21","Armies at Panipat"],["1526-04-21","Mughal artillery devastates"],["1526-04-21","Ibrahim Lodi killed"],["1526","Delhi and Agra captured"],["1530","Mughal Empire established"]]);
a("Third Battle of Panipat","1761-01-14","1761-01-14","India",["Battle","Early Modern War"],"The Third Battle of Panipat in 1761 saw Afghan forces under Ahmad Shah Durrani defeat the Maratha Confederacy in one of the 18th century's bloodiest battles. An estimated 40,000-100,000 died, ending Maratha supremacy and creating a power vacuum for the British.",[["1758","Marathas expand into Punjab"],["1759","Durrani invades India"],["1761-01-14","Massive battle at Panipat"],["1761-01-14","Afghan reserves turn tide"],["1761-01-14","40,000-100,000 killed"],["1761","Maratha power broken"]]);
a("Battle of White Mountain","1620-11-08","1620-11-08","Bohemia",["Battle","Thirty Years War"],"The Battle of White Mountain in 1620 was an early decisive Thirty Years' War engagement. Catholic League forces crushed the Bohemian Protestant army in two hours, ending the Bohemian Revolt and leading to forced re-Catholicization.",[["1618","Defenestration of Prague"],["1619","Frederick V elected king"],["1620-11-08","Catholic League attacks"],["1620-11-08","Battle lasts two hours"],["1620","Frederick flees"],["1627","Re-Catholicization of Bohemia"]]);
a("Battle of Sarhu","1619-04-14","1619-04-18","Manchuria",["Battle","Early Modern War"],"The Battle of Sarhu in 1619 was Nurhaci's decisive victory over Ming China. He defeated four Ming columns by concentrating forces against each in turn. The victory established Manchu military dominance and set the stage for the Qing conquest of China.",[["1616","Nurhaci establishes Later Jin"],["1619","Ming sends 100,000+ in four columns"],["1619-04-14","First column destroyed"],["1619-04-17","Third column defeated"],["1619","Ming loses 45,000+ troops"],["1644","Qing conquer China"]]);
a("Battle of Cajamarca","1532-11-16","1532-11-16","Peru",["Battle","Colonial Conquest"],"The Battle of Cajamarca in 1532 toppled the Inca Empire. Pizarro's 168 conquistadors captured Emperor Atahualpa amid his 80,000-strong army through surprise, firearms, and cavalry. The capture destroyed the Inca Empire.",[["1531","Pizarro's third expedition"],["1532","Pizarro marches into Andes"],["1532-11-16","Spanish ambush Inca"],["1532-11-16","Atahualpa captured"],["1533","Atahualpa executed"],["1533","Cusco captured"]]);
a("Siege of Tenochtitlan","1521-05-26","1521-08-13","Mexico",["Siege","Colonial Conquest"],"The Siege of Tenochtitlan in 1521 was the conquest of the Aztec Empire. Cortés and indigenous allies besieged the capital for 80 days. Combined with smallpox, the siege destroyed Aztec civilization and established Spanish rule over Mexico.",[["1519","Cortés arrives in Mexico"],["1520","Noche Triste; Spanish expelled"],["1521-05-26","Siege begins"],["1521","Smallpox devastates defenders"],["1521-08-13","City falls"],["1521","Aztec Empire destroyed"]]);

// --- NAPOLEONIC ---
a("Battle of Trafalgar","1805-10-21","1805-10-21","Europe",["Battle","Naval Battle"],"The Battle of Trafalgar in 1805 was a decisive British naval victory. Admiral Nelson destroyed the Franco-Spanish fleet, ensuring British naval supremacy for a century. Nelson was mortally wounded but lived to learn of victory.",[["1805","Napoleon plans invasion"],["1805-10-21","Nelson attacks in two columns"],["1805-10-21","'England expects' signal"],["1805-10-21","Nelson fatally wounded"],["1805-10-21","Fleet destroyed"],["1805","Invasion abandoned"]]);
a("Battle of Austerlitz","1805-12-02","1805-12-02","Europe",["Battle","Napoleonic War"],"The Battle of Austerlitz (Three Emperors) in 1805 was Napoleon's greatest victory. He feigned weakness to draw allies into a trap, then struck their center at Pratzen Heights. The victory forced Austria from the Third Coalition.",[["1805-10","Austria defeated at Ulm"],["1805-11","Vienna occupied"],["1805-12-02","Napoleon feigns weakness"],["1805-12-02","Strike at Pratzen Heights"],["1805-12-02","Coalition army destroyed"],["1805-12","Treaty of Pressburg"]]);
a("Battle of Borodino","1812-09-07","1812-09-07","Russia",["Battle","Napoleonic War"],"The Battle of Borodino in 1812 was the bloodiest single day of the Napoleonic Wars with 70,000+ casualties. Napoleon's Grande Armée fought Kutuzov near Moscow in a pyrrhic victory that marked the beginning of the disastrous Russian campaign.",[["1812-06","Napoleon invades with 600,000"],["1812","Scorched-earth retreat"],["1812-09-07","Stand at Borodino"],["1812-09-07","70,000+ casualties"],["1812-09-14","Napoleon enters Moscow"],["1812-12","Only 27,000 return"]]);
a("Battle of Waterloo","1815-06-18","1815-06-18","Europe",["Battle","Napoleonic War"],"The Battle of Waterloo in 1815 was Napoleon's final defeat. Wellington's Anglo-allied army, reinforced by Blücher's Prussians, defeated Napoleon near Brussels. The battle ended the Napoleonic era and ushered in a century of relative European peace.",[["1815-03","Napoleon escapes Elba"],["1815-06-16","Ligny; Prussians defeated"],["1815-06-18","Wellington holds at Waterloo"],["1815-06-18","Prussians arrive"],["1815-06-18","Imperial Guard repulsed"],["1815-10","Napoleon exiled to St. Helena"]]);
a("Battle of Leipzig","1813-10-16","1813-10-19","Europe",["Battle","Napoleonic War"],"The Battle of Leipzig (Battle of the Nations) in 1813 was the largest battle before WWI, with 500,000 soldiers engaged. The coalition defeated Napoleon, forcing his retreat to France and first abdication.",[["1813","Sixth Coalition forms"],["1813-10-16","Battle begins"],["1813-10-18","Coalition massive attack"],["1813-10-18","Saxon allies defect"],["1813-10-19","Napoleon retreats"],["1814-04","Napoleon abdicates"]]);
a("Battle of the Nile","1798-08-01","1798-08-02","Egypt",["Battle","Naval Battle"],"The Battle of the Nile in 1798 was a decisive British victory when Nelson destroyed the French fleet at Aboukir Bay, stranding Napoleon's army in Egypt. The victory established British Mediterranean naval dominance.",[["1798","Napoleon sails for Egypt"],["1798-08-01","Nelson finds French fleet"],["1798-08-01","British attack from both sides"],["1798-08-02","Flagship L'Orient explodes"],["1798","11 of 13 French ships taken"],["1799","Napoleon abandons Egypt"]]);
a("Battle of Jena-Auerstedt","1806-10-14","1806-10-14","Prussia",["Battle","Napoleonic War"],"The twin Battles of Jena and Auerstedt in 1806 shattered the Prussian army. Napoleon won at Jena while Davout's single corps defeated the main Prussian army despite 2-to-1 odds. The campaign led to Berlin's occupation.",[["1806-10","Napoleon invades Prussia"],["1806-10-14","Napoleon wins at Jena"],["1806-10-14","Davout wins at Auerstedt"],["1806-10-14","Prussian army shattered"],["1806-10-27","Napoleon enters Berlin"],["1807","Treaty of Tilsit"]]);
a("Battle of Wagram","1809-07-05","1809-07-06","Austria",["Battle","Napoleonic War"],"The Battle of Wagram in 1809 with 300,000 troops was one of the largest Napoleonic battles. Napoleon defeated Archduke Charles after two days of fighting near Vienna, ending the Fifth Coalition.",[["1809-04","Austria attacks; Fifth Coalition"],["1809-05","Napoleon takes Vienna"],["1809-05-21","Aspern-Essling; repulsed"],["1809-07-05","Napoleon crosses Danube"],["1809-07-06","French break Austrian line"],["1809-10","Treaty of Schönbrunn"]]);
a("Ulm Campaign","1805-09-25","1805-10-20","Austria",["Battle","Napoleonic War"],"The Ulm Campaign in October 1805 was Napoleon's brilliant maneuver that encircled an Austrian army without major battle. Through rapid marching and deception, Napoleon trapped 30,000 troops, opening the road to Austerlitz.",[["1805-08","Austria joins Third Coalition"],["1805-09","Napoleon wheels army to Rhine"],["1805-10-07","French cross Danube behind Austrians"],["1805-10-17","Mack realizes encirclement"],["1805-10-20","30,000 surrender at Ulm"],["1805-12","Austerlitz follows"]]);

// --- AMERICAN CIVIL WAR ---
a("Battle of Gettysburg","1863-07-01","1863-07-03","United States",["Battle","American Civil War"],"The Battle of Gettysburg in 1863 was the bloodiest Civil War battle and a turning point. Lee's invasion was defeated; Pickett's Charge on the final day was a devastating failure that effectively ended Confederate hopes.",[["1863-06","Lee invades Pennsylvania"],["1863-07-01","Forces collide"],["1863-07-02","Little Round Top"],["1863-07-03","Pickett's Charge fails"],["1863-07-04","Lee retreats"],["1863-11-19","Gettysburg Address"]]);
a("Battle of Antietam","1862-09-17","1862-09-17","United States",["Battle","American Civil War"],"The Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, was the bloodiest single day in American military history with 23,000 casualties. Lee's retreat gave Lincoln the opportunity to issue the Emancipation Proclamation.",[["1862-09","Lee invades Maryland"],["1862-09-13","Lee's lost orders found"],["1862-09-17","Battle rages across three sectors"],["1862-09-17","23,000 casualties"],["1862-09-18","Lee retreats"],["1862-09-22","Emancipation Proclamation"]]);
a("Siege of Vicksburg","1863-05-18","1863-07-04","United States",["Siege","American Civil War"],"The Siege of Vicksburg in 1863 was a decisive Union victory. Grant's brilliant campaign and 47-day siege captured the Confederate fortress on the Mississippi, splitting the Confederacy in two.",[["1863-03","Campaign begins"],["1863-05","Five victories in 17 days"],["1863-05-18","Siege begins"],["1863-07-04","Garrison surrenders"],["1863-07-09","Port Hudson falls"],["1863","Union controls Mississippi"]]);
a("Battle of Shiloh","1862-04-06","1862-04-07","United States",["Battle","American Civil War"],"The Battle of Shiloh in 1862 was a major early Civil War battle. Confederate surprise attack nearly overwhelmed Grant, but Union reinforcements won the counterattack. The 23,000 casualties shocked the nation and ended hopes for a quick war.",[["1862-04-06","Confederate surprise attack"],["1862-04-06","Albert Sidney Johnston killed"],["1862-04-06","Union pushed to river"],["1862-04-07","Buell's reinforcements arrive"],["1862-04-07","Grant counterattacks"],["1862","Both sides realize war will be long"]]);
a("Battle of Fredericksburg","1862-12-11","1862-12-15","United States",["Battle","American Civil War"],"The Battle of Fredericksburg in 1862 was a devastating Union defeat. Burnside's 14 futile charges against the stone wall on Marye's Heights resulted in 12,000 Union casualties in one of the most lopsided Confederate victories.",[["1862-11","Burnside replaces McClellan"],["1862-12-11","Union crosses Rappahannock"],["1862-12-13","Frontal assaults at Marye's Heights"],["1862-12-13","14 failed charges"],["1862-12-13","12,000+ Union casualties"],["1863-01","Burnside replaced"]]);
a("Battle of Chancellorsville","1863-04-30","1863-05-06","United States",["Battle","American Civil War"],"The Battle of Chancellorsville in 1863 was Lee's tactical masterpiece. Outnumbered 2-to-1, he divided forces and sent Jackson on a devastating flank attack. The victory was marred by Jackson's death from friendly fire.",[["1863-04-30","Hooker moves through Wilderness"],["1863-05-01","Lee divides forces"],["1863-05-02","Jackson's flank attack"],["1863-05-02","Jackson wounded by friendly fire"],["1863-05-06","Union retreats"],["1863-05-10","Jackson dies"]]);
a("Siege of Petersburg","1864-06-09","1865-03-25","United States",["Siege","American Civil War"],"The Siege of Petersburg from 1864 to 1865 was the Civil War's longest siege. Grant's trench warfare exhausted Lee's army over nine months, leading to Richmond's fall and Lee's surrender.",[["1864-06","Initial attacks fail"],["1864-07-30","Battle of the Crater"],["1864","Trenches extend for miles"],["1865-03-25","Fort Stedman fails"],["1865-04-01","Five Forks"],["1865-04-02","Petersburg falls"]]);
a("Battle of Fort Sumter","1861-04-12","1861-04-14","United States",["Battle","American Civil War"],"The bombardment of Fort Sumter on April 12-14, 1861, was the opening engagement of the American Civil War. Confederate forces bombarded the Union garrison in Charleston Harbor for 34 hours. Major Anderson surrendered without casualties, but the attack unified the North and began four years of devastating warfare.",[["1860-12","South Carolina secedes"],["1861-01","Southern states seize federal forts"],["1861-04-12","Confederate bombardment begins"],["1861-04-13","Fort catches fire"],["1861-04-14","Anderson surrenders"],["1861-04-15","Lincoln calls for 75,000 volunteers"]]);

// --- WORLD WAR I ---
a("Battle of Verdun","1916-02-21","1916-12-18","France",["Battle","World War I"],"The Battle of Verdun from February to December 1916 was WWI's longest battle. Germany's plan to 'bleed France white' produced 700,000+ casualties but the French held under Pétain's cry 'They shall not pass!' The battle symbolizes WWI's futility.",[["1916-02-21","German offensive begins"],["1916-02-25","Fort Douaumont captured"],["1916-02","Pétain organizes supply route"],["1916-07","Somme draws resources"],["1916-10-24","Douaumont recaptured"],["1916-12-18","Battle ends unchanged"]]);
a("Battle of the Somme","1916-07-01","1916-11-18","France",["Battle","World War I"],"The Battle of the Somme in 1916 was one of the bloodiest battles ever. The British suffered 57,470 casualties on the first day alone. Over 1 million total casualties for 10km of advance. It saw the first use of tanks.",[["1916-07-01","57,470 British casualties day one"],["1916-09-15","First tanks used"],["1916-10","Diminishing returns"],["1916-11-18","Battle ends"],["1916","1 million+ casualties for 10km"],["1917","German withdrawal"]]);
a("Battle of Passchendaele","1917-07-31","1917-11-10","Belgium",["Battle","World War I"],"Passchendaele (Third Ypres) in 1917 epitomized WWI's futility. Torrential rain turned the battlefield into impassable mud. 475,000 casualties for 8km of advance that Germany retook months later.",[["1917-07-31","Offensive begins in rain"],["1917-08","Battlefield becomes mud"],["1917-10","Canadians assigned"],["1917-11-06","Village captured"],["1917-11-10","Battle ends"],["1918-04","Germans retake all ground"]]);
a("Gallipoli Campaign","1915-02-19","1916-01-09","Ottoman Empire",["Battle","World War I"],"The Gallipoli Campaign was a failed Allied attempt to reach Russia through Ottoman territory. ANZAC, British, and French troops couldn't advance against Mustafa Kemal's defense. 500,000 casualties. It became a founding myth for Australia, New Zealand, and Turkey.",[["1915-02-19","Naval bombardment begins"],["1915-03-18","Naval attack fails"],["1915-04-25","ANZAC landing"],["1915-04-25","Mustafa Kemal rallies defense"],["1915-08","Suvla Bay fails"],["1916-01-09","Evacuation complete"]]);
a("Battle of Jutland","1916-05-31","1916-06-01","Europe",["Battle","Naval Battle"],"The Battle of Jutland in 1916 was WWI's largest naval battle. Though Germany inflicted heavier losses, the strategic outcome favored Britain as the German fleet never again sought major engagement.",[["1916-05-31","German fleet sorties"],["1916-05-31","Three British battlecruisers lost"],["1916-05-31","Jellicoe deploys Grand Fleet"],["1916-06-01","Germans escape"],["1916","German fleet stays in port"],["1918","German fleet mutinies"]]);
a("Battle of Tannenberg 1914","1914-08-26","1914-08-30","East Prussia",["Battle","World War I"],"The Battle of Tannenberg in 1914 was a decisive German Eastern Front victory. Hindenburg and Ludendorff encircled the Russian Second Army, capturing 92,000 soldiers. General Samsonov committed suicide.",[["1914-08","Russia invades East Prussia"],["1914-08-22","Hindenburg takes command"],["1914-08-26","Germans concentrate forces"],["1914-08-29","Russians surrounded"],["1914-08-30","Samsonov commits suicide"],["1914-08-30","92,000 captured"]]);
a("First Battle of the Marne","1914-09-05","1914-09-12","France",["Battle","World War I"],"The First Marne in 1914 saved Paris and halted the German advance. French taxis rushed reinforcements to the front. The German retreat ended the Schlieffen Plan and led to trench warfare.",[["1914-08","Germans advance through Belgium"],["1914-09-04","Gallieni spots opportunity"],["1914-09-05","Counterattack launched"],["1914-09-07","Taxis ferry 6,000 troops"],["1914-09-12","Germans retreat"],["1914","Trench warfare begins"]]);
a("Battle of Sarikamish","1914-12-22","1915-01-17","Turkey",["Battle","World War I"],"The Battle of Sarikamish was a catastrophic Ottoman defeat in the Caucasus. Enver Pasha's poorly planned winter offensive lost 90,000 troops, mostly to cold. The defeat contributed to the Armenian Genocide.",[["1914-11","Ottomans enter WWI"],["1914-12-22","Winter offensive launched"],["1915-01","Freezing temperatures decimate troops"],["1915-01","Russian counterattack"],["1915-01-17","90,000 Ottoman casualties"],["1915","Armenian Genocide begins"]]);
a("Battle of Vimy Ridge","1917-04-09","1917-04-12","France",["Battle","World War I"],"The Battle of Vimy Ridge in 1917 was a landmark Canadian victory. The Canadian Corps captured the fortified German position through meticulous planning. The battle is a defining moment of Canadian national identity.",[["1917-04","Elaborate preparation"],["1917-04-09","Four divisions attack together"],["1917-04-09","Creeping barrage covers advance"],["1917-04-12","All objectives taken"],["1917","3,598 Canadians killed"],["1936","Vimy Memorial dedicated"]]);
a("Battle of Cambrai","1917-11-20","1917-12-07","France",["Battle","World War I"],"The Battle of Cambrai in 1917 was the first large-scale tank assault. 476 British tanks broke through the Hindenburg Line, achieving the deepest Western Front advance. However, German counterattack recaptured most ground.",[["1917-11-20","476 tanks attack"],["1917-11-20","Hindenburg Line breached"],["1917-11-20","Deepest single-day advance"],["1917-11-30","German counterattack"],["1917-12-07","Most ground recaptured"],["1918","Tank tactics refined"]]);
a("Battle of Amiens 1918","1918-08-08","1918-08-12","France",["Battle","World War I"],"The Battle of Amiens in 1918 opened the Hundred Days Offensive. British, Australian, and Canadian forces with 500 tanks achieved a stunning breakthrough. Ludendorff called it 'the black day of the German Army.'",[["1918-08-08","Surprise attack near Amiens"],["1918-08-08","500 tanks lead assault"],["1918-08-08","13km advance in one day"],["1918-08-08","'Black day of German Army'"],["1918-09","Hindenburg Line breached"],["1918-11-11","Armistice"]]);
a("Dardanelles Naval Attack","1915-03-18","1915-03-18","Turkey",["Battle","Naval Battle"],"The Allied naval attack on the Dardanelles in 1915 was a disastrous attempt to force the straits. Three battleships were sunk by Ottoman mines and three more crippled, leading to the fateful decision to land at Gallipoli.",[["1915-02-19","Bombardment of outer forts"],["1915-03-18","Main fleet attacks"],["1915-03-18","Bouvet sinks"],["1915-03-18","Irresistible and Ocean lost"],["1915-03","Naval attack abandoned"],["1915-04","Ground invasion planned"]]);

// --- WORLD WAR II ---
a("Battle of Stalingrad","1942-08-23","1943-02-02","Soviet Union",["Battle","World War II"],"The Battle of Stalingrad was history's largest and bloodiest battle with nearly 2 million casualties. The Soviet encirclement of the German 6th Army marked WWII's Eastern Front turning point and shattered the myth of Wehrmacht invincibility.",[["1942-08-23","German bombardment"],["1942-09","Street fighting begins"],["1942-11-19","Operation Uranus encircles Germans"],["1942-12","Relief attempt fails"],["1943-01-31","Paulus surrenders"],["1943-02-02","Last resistance ends"]]);
a("Battle of Midway","1942-06-04","1942-06-07","Pacific Ocean",["Battle","Naval Battle"],"The Battle of Midway in 1942 was the Pacific War's decisive naval battle. American aircraft sank four Japanese carriers while losing one. Achieved through codebreaking and bravery, it shifted Pacific power permanently.",[["1942-05","Codebreakers identify target"],["1942-06-04","Japanese strike Midway"],["1942-06-04","US dive bombers find carriers"],["1942-06-04","Three carriers sunk in 5 minutes"],["1942-06-05","Hiryu sunk"],["1942","Japanese offensive capability crippled"]]);
a("Battle of Kursk","1943-07-05","1943-07-23","Soviet Union",["Battle","World War II"],"The Battle of Kursk in 1943 was the largest tank battle in history. Soviet forces, forewarned by intelligence, built deep defenses against Operation Citadel. After Kursk, the Wehrmacht was in continuous retreat until Berlin fell.",[["1943-07-05","German offensive begins"],["1943-07-12","Tank battle at Prokhorovka"],["1943-07-12","Advance halted"],["1943-07-13","Hitler cancels operation"],["1943-07-17","Soviet counteroffensives"],["1943-08","Kharkov recaptured"]]);
a("D-Day Normandy Invasion","1944-06-06","1944-06-06","France",["Battle","World War II"],"D-Day on June 6, 1944, was history's largest amphibious invasion. Allied forces landed on five Normandy beaches despite fierce resistance, especially at Omaha Beach. 156,000 troops landed, leading to France's liberation.",[["1943","Overlord planning begins"],["1944-06-05","Eisenhower decides to launch"],["1944-06-06","Airborne troops land"],["1944-06-06","Five beach landings"],["1944-06-06","156,000 troops land"],["1944-08-25","Paris liberated"]]);
a("Battle of the Bulge","1944-12-16","1945-01-25","Europe",["Battle","World War II"],"The Battle of the Bulge was WWII's last major German offensive. Hitler's Ardennes surprise created a dangerous 'bulge' in Allied lines. Despite Bastogne's siege, Patton's counterattack eliminated the salient and exhausted Germany's reserves.",[["1944-12-16","German surprise attack"],["1944-12-20","101st surrounded at Bastogne"],["1944-12-22","McAuliffe: 'Nuts!'"],["1944-12-26","Patton relieves Bastogne"],["1945-01","Bulge eliminated"],["1945-05","Germany surrenders"]]);
a("Second Battle of El Alamein","1942-10-23","1942-11-11","Egypt",["Battle","World War II"],"The Second Battle of El Alamein in 1942 was North Africa's decisive engagement. Montgomery defeated Rommel's Afrika Korps, preventing Axis seizure of the Suez Canal. Churchill: 'Before Alamein we never had a victory.'",[["1942-08","Montgomery takes command"],["1942-10-23","Lightfoot begins"],["1942-11-02","Supercharge breaks through"],["1942-11-04","Rommel retreats"],["1942-11-08","Operation Torch"],["1943-05","Axis surrender in Africa"]]);
a("Battle of Iwo Jima","1945-02-19","1945-03-26","Japan",["Battle","World War II"],"The Battle of Iwo Jima in 1945 was one of the Pacific War's bloodiest. Marines assaulted the fortified island with its tunnel network. The iconic flag-raising on Mt. Suribachi is among WWII's most recognized images.",[["1945-02-19","Marines land"],["1945-02-23","Flag on Suribachi"],["1945-03","Fighting through tunnels"],["1945-03-26","Island secured"],["1945","6,800 Americans killed"],["1945","18,000+ Japanese killed"]]);
a("Battle of Okinawa","1945-04-01","1945-06-22","Japan",["Battle","World War II"],"The Battle of Okinawa in 1945 was the Pacific's bloodiest battle. The 82-day campaign included massive kamikaze attacks. Over 200,000 total killed, including 100,000 civilians, which influenced the decision to use atomic bombs.",[["1945-04-01","US forces land"],["1945-04-06","Mass kamikaze attacks"],["1945-04-07","Yamato sunk"],["1945-05","Shuri Line fighting"],["1945-06-22","Resistance ends"],["1945","200,000+ total killed"]]);
a("Battle of Britain","1940-07-10","1940-10-31","United Kingdom",["Battle","World War II"],"The Battle of Britain in 1940 was the first campaign fought entirely by air. The RAF, aided by radar, defended Britain against the Luftwaffe. Churchill praised 'The Few.' It was Hitler's first major defeat.",[["1940-06","Britain stands alone"],["1940-07-10","Battle begins"],["1940-08","RAF airfields targeted"],["1940-08-20","'The Few' speech"],["1940-09-07","London Blitz begins"],["1940-10","Hitler postpones invasion"]]);
a("Battle of the Atlantic","1939-09-03","1945-05-08","Atlantic Ocean",["Battle","World War II"],"The Battle of the Atlantic was WWII's longest campaign. German U-boats tried to sever Allied supply lines. The Allies won through sonar, radar, codebreaking, and convoy tactics. 70,000 Allied seamen were lost.",[["1939","Submarine warfare begins"],["1942","Massive Allied shipping losses"],["1943-03","Crisis month"],["1943-05","Black May: 43 U-boats sunk"],["1943","Technology overcomes U-boats"],["1945","783 U-boats lost total"]]);
a("Attack on Pearl Harbor","1941-12-07","1941-12-07","United States",["Battle","World War II"],"The attack on Pearl Harbor on December 7, 1941, was Japan's surprise strike against the US naval base in Hawaii. 2,403 Americans were killed and 21 ships damaged. Roosevelt called it 'a date which will live in infamy,' bringing the US into WWII.",[["1941","US-Japan relations deteriorate"],["1941-12-07","First wave attacks"],["1941-12-07","USS Arizona explodes"],["1941-12-07","2,403 killed"],["1941-12-08","Congress declares war"],["1941-12-11","Germany declares war on US"]]);
a("Battle of Berlin 1945","1945-04-16","1945-05-02","Germany",["Battle","World War II"],"The Battle of Berlin in 1945 was WWII's final European offensive. Soviet forces stormed Berlin in brutal urban warfare. Hitler committed suicide April 30; Berlin surrendered May 2, ending Nazi Germany.",[["1945-04-16","Soviet offensive begins"],["1945-04-25","Berlin encircled"],["1945-04-30","Hitler commits suicide"],["1945-05-02","Berlin surrenders"],["1945-05-08","V-E Day"],["1945","350,000 combined casualties"]]);
a("Fall of France 1940","1940-05-10","1940-06-25","France",["Battle","World War II"],"The Fall of France in 1940 was Germany's Blitzkrieg conquest in just six weeks. Panzers broke through the Ardennes, the BEF evacuated at Dunkirk, and France signed an armistice. The disaster left Britain alone against Nazi Germany.",[["1940-05-10","Germany invades"],["1940-05-13","Panzers cross Meuse"],["1940-05-26","Dunkirk evacuation"],["1940-06-04","338,000 evacuated"],["1940-06-14","Germans enter Paris"],["1940-06-22","Armistice signed"]]);
a("Operation Barbarossa","1941-06-22","1941-12-05","Soviet Union",["Battle","World War II"],"Operation Barbarossa in 1941 was the German invasion of the Soviet Union—history's largest military operation. 3.8 million troops attacked on a 2,900-km front. Despite initial success, the offensive stalled before Moscow, opening the Eastern Front.",[["1941-06-22","3.8 million troops invade"],["1941-07","Smolensk captured"],["1941-09","Leningrad besieged"],["1941-10","Drive on Moscow"],["1941-12-05","Soviet counteroffensive"],["1941","Blitzkrieg fails"]]);
a("Siege of Leningrad","1941-09-08","1944-01-27","Soviet Union",["Siege","World War II"],"The Siege of Leningrad lasted 872 days—one of history's longest and most destructive sieges. 1 million civilians died, mostly from famine. Supply came via the 'Road of Life' across frozen Lake Ladoga.",[["1941-09-08","Encirclement complete"],["1941-11","Rations drop to 125g"],["1941-12","Road of Life opens"],["1942","650,000 die of starvation"],["1943-01","Partial blockade break"],["1944-01-27","Full liberation"]]);
a("Dunkirk Evacuation","1940-05-26","1940-06-04","France",["Battle","World War II"],"The Dunkirk evacuation in 1940 rescued 338,000 Allied soldiers from northern France. Military vessels and civilian 'Little Ships' crossed the Channel under air attack. Though a defeat, it preserved the British Army and created the 'Dunkirk spirit.'",[["1940-05-20","Germans reach Channel"],["1940-05-24","Hitler's halt order"],["1940-05-26","Evacuation begins"],["1940-06-01","Little Ships join"],["1940-06-04","338,000 evacuated"],["1940-06-04","'Fight on the beaches' speech"]]);
a("Fall of Singapore","1942-02-08","1942-02-15","Singapore",["Battle","World War II"],"The Fall of Singapore in 1942 was Britain's greatest military defeat. Japan conquered the 'impregnable' fortress in one week, capturing 80,000 troops—the largest British surrender ever. It shattered European colonial prestige in Asia.",[["1941-12-08","Malaya invasion begins"],["1942-01","Rapid Japanese advance"],["1942-02-08","Japanese cross Johor Strait"],["1942-02-15","80,000 troops surrender"],["1942","Colonial prestige shattered"],["1945-09","Singapore liberated"]]);
a("Battle of Guadalcanal","1942-08-07","1943-02-09","Solomon Islands",["Battle","World War II"],"Guadalcanal from 1942-1943 was the first major Allied Pacific offensive. Marines fought months of jungle warfare for a critical airfield. The campaign included fierce naval battles in 'Ironbottom Sound' and began Japan's long retreat.",[["1942-08-07","Marines land"],["1942-08","Henderson Field secured"],["1942-10-25","Japanese assault repulsed"],["1942-11","Naval battles"],["1943-01","Japanese evacuate"],["1943-02-09","Island secured"]]);
a("Battle of Coral Sea","1942-05-04","1942-05-08","Pacific Ocean",["Battle","Naval Battle"],"The Battle of Coral Sea in 1942 was the first naval battle where ships never sighted each other. Though a tactical draw, it was a strategic Allied victory that turned back Japan's Port Moresby invasion—the first check on Japanese expansion.",[["1942-05","Japanese plan Port Moresby invasion"],["1942-05-07","Carrier Shoho sunk"],["1942-05-08","Carriers exchange strikes"],["1942-05-08","Lexington sunk; Shokaku damaged"],["1942-05-08","Invasion cancelled"],["1942-06","Damaged carriers miss Midway"]]);
a("Battle of Leyte Gulf","1944-10-23","1944-10-26","Philippines",["Battle","Naval Battle"],"The Battle of Leyte Gulf in 1944 was history's largest naval battle. The US Navy destroyed the Japanese fleet in four engagements around the Philippines. It saw the first kamikaze attacks and ended Japan as a naval power.",[["1944-10-20","MacArthur returns"],["1944-10-24","Musashi sunk"],["1944-10-25","Battle off Samar"],["1944-10-25","Surigao Strait"],["1944-10-25","First kamikaze attacks"],["1944-10-26","Japanese retreat"]]);
a("Battle of Imphal and Kohima","1944-03-08","1944-07-22","India",["Battle","World War II"],"The Battles of Imphal and Kohima in 1944 stopped Japan's invasion of India. Called 'the Stalingrad of the East,' the British-Indian victory cost Japan 53,000 casualties in what Japan called its greatest land defeat.",[["1944-03-08","Japanese Operation U-Go"],["1944-04","Kohima besieged"],["1944-04","Imphal surrounded"],["1944-05","Kohima relieved"],["1944-07-22","Japanese withdraw"],["1944","53,000 Japanese casualties"]]);
a("Siege of Sevastopol 1941","1941-10-30","1942-07-04","Soviet Union",["Siege","World War II"],"The Siege of Sevastopol from 1941-1942 saw Germany deploy the largest siege gun ever built, 'Schwerer Gustav,' against the Soviet naval base. After 250 days of fierce resistance, the garrison was overwhelmed.",[["1941-10-30","Siege begins"],["1941-12","First assault repulsed"],["1942-06","Major assault with Schwerer Gustav"],["1942-07-04","Resistance ends"],["1942","Germany controls Crimea"],["1944","Soviets recapture city"]]);

