a("Hundred Years War","1337-05-24","1453-10-19","Europe",["War","Medieval War"],"The Hundred Years' War (1337-1453) between England and France saw dramatic shifts including English victories at Crécy and Agincourt, followed by French revival under Joan of Arc. It ended feudal armies and fostered national identities.",[["1337","War begins"],["1346","Crécy"],["1415","Agincourt"],["1429","Joan of Arc"],["1431","Joan burned"],["1453","France wins"]]);
a("Thirty Years War","1618-05-23","1648-10-24","Europe",["War","Early Modern War"],"The Thirty Years' War (1618-1648) killed 8 million—one-third of Germany's population. Starting as religious conflict, it ended with the Peace of Westphalia, establishing the modern concept of state sovereignty.",[["1618","Defenestration of Prague"],["1630","Swedish intervention"],["1631","Sack of Magdeburg"],["1635","France enters"],["1648","Peace of Westphalia"],["1648","Modern sovereignty concept"]]);
a("Seven Years War","1756-05-17","1763-02-10","Global",["War","Early Modern War"],"The Seven Years' War (1756-1763) was the first 'world war,' fought across continents. Britain's victories established it as the dominant colonial power. The financial burden contributed to both the American and French Revolutions.",[["1756","War begins"],["1757","Plassey; British power in India"],["1759","Year of Victories"],["1760","Montreal falls"],["1763","Treaty of Paris"],["1763","Britain dominant"]]);
a("Napoleonic Wars","1803-05-18","1815-11-20","Europe",["War","Napoleonic War"],"The Napoleonic Wars (1803-1815) saw Napoleon conquer much of Europe, spreading revolutionary ideals and the Napoleonic Code. The 1812 Russian campaign and Waterloo ended his reign. The Congress of Vienna reshaped European borders.",[["1805","Trafalgar and Austerlitz"],["1808","Peninsular War"],["1812","Russian campaign fails"],["1813","Leipzig"],["1815","Waterloo"],["1815","Congress of Vienna"]]);
